{{Infobox book | name = Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy | image = Fallout - An American Nuclear Tragedy.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = | author = [[Philip L. Fradkin]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = [[Nuclear fallout]] | genre = | publisher = University of Arizona Press | pub_date = 1989 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 300 pp. | isbn = 978-0-8165-1086-3 | oclc = 18521228 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy''''' is a 1989 book by [[Philip L. Fradkin]] which was republished in a second edition in 2004. The book is about the [[Ionizing radiation|radiation exposure]] of people and their livestock living [[downwinders|downwind]] from the [[nuclear weapons testing]] at the [[Nevada Test Site]] in the 1950s.<ref name=am>Luther J. Carter. [https://www.jstor.org/pss/1963565 Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy (Review)] ''The American Political Science Review'', Vol. 84, No. 2 (June 1990), pp. 657-658.</ref> The case of ''Irene Allen et al. vs. the United States'' is used as a framework for the narrative.<ref>Renée H. Guillory. [https://www.jstor.org/pss/40023717 Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy (Review)] ''Journal of the Arizona-Nevada Academy of Science'', Vol. 27, No. 1 (1993), p. 161.</ref> The court case "resulted in an award of $2.66 million in damages to eight persons with [[leukemia]], one with [[thyroid cancer]], and another with [[breast cancer]]".<ref>Henry N. Wagner. [http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/summary/262/5/699 Fallout: An American Nuclear Tragedy (Review)], ''JAMA'', 1989;262(5):699.</ref>
Philip Fradkin is an American [[environmentalist]] historian, journalist and author. Fradkin shared a [[Pulitzer Prize]] awarded to the metropolitan staff of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' for coverage of the [[Watts riots]] in 1965.<ref name=am/><ref>[http://www.philipfradkin.com/index.htm Philip L. Fradkin Biography]</ref>
